# Decampify — write-scoped R2 credentials, used ONLY by `npm run upload`.
# Copy to .env.upload (git-ignored). NEVER commit the real .env.upload, and never
# add these values to Vercel — the deployed site has no reason to write to R2.
#
# Why this is a separate file from .env:
# The site's own R2 token (R2_ACCESS_KEY_ID in .env) is deliberately *Object Read only*.
# It signs download URLs and nothing else, so if it ever leaked it could not overwrite
# or delete your masters. That also means it cannot upload — every PUT returns
# AccessDenied. Uploading needs its own short-lived Object Read & Write token.
#
# How to mint one:
#   1. Cloudflare dashboard -> R2 -> API -> Create API token
#   2. Permissions: Object Read & Write, scoped to your bucket only
#   3. Copy this file to .env.upload and paste the values below
#   4. npm run upload:check   (dry run — writes nothing)   then   npm run upload
#   5. DELETE the token in Cloudflare once the upload is finished
#
# Step 5 matters: this token can overwrite and delete everything in the bucket. Treat it
# as disposable — mint one per upload session, revoke it when you are done. If a later
# run fails with an auth error, the token was almost certainly revoked; mint a new one.
#
# `npm run upload` reads .env and .env.upload together, so you only put the upload
# token here — bucket, endpoint and the rest keep living in .env.

R2_UPLOAD_ACCESS_KEY_ID=<replace with new temporary key>
R2_UPLOAD_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=<replace with new temporary secret>

# Optional — where your staged audio lives, relative to the project root.
# Defaults to _uploads/ ; the folder must mirror your R2 key paths exactly, e.g.
#   _uploads/stream/My-EP/Artist_Name-Track_One.mp3
# R2_STAGING_DIR=_uploads

# Optional — upload tuning. Defaults are fine on a solid connection. On a flaky link,
# large bundles can fail mid-transfer with a TLS "bad record mac" error; going serial
# and raising the attempts is what gets them through:
#   UPLOAD_CONCURRENCY=1 UPLOAD_QUEUE_SIZE=1 UPLOAD_ATTEMPTS=8 npm run upload
# UPLOAD_ATTEMPTS=4        # whole-object attempts, backing off 2s / 4s / 8s...
# UPLOAD_PART_ATTEMPTS=8   # retries per individual 16 MB part
# UPLOAD_CONCURRENCY=3     # files uploaded in parallel
# UPLOAD_QUEUE_SIZE=4      # parts uploaded in parallel within one file
